{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CdHDfopXGVYsJbyqXfp3V","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 4 tests pass, including the new consecutive-dots rejection and multi-label acceptance.\n\n## Summary\n\n**Root cause:** In `src/validate.js`, the domain-label group used `*` instead of `+`:\n\n```\n(\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]*)*    →    (\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]+)*\n```\n\nWith `*`, a dot followed by an empty label was a valid match, so consecutive dots (`mail..example.com`) slipped through — directly contradicting the function's own doc comment that labels must be non-empty. The shipped test suite only checked a single-label domain (`example.com`) and a no-`@` case, so it never exercised the empty-label path and passed for months.\n\n**Fix:** Changed the quantifier to `+`, requiring each domain label to have at least one character.\n\n**Tests added** (written to fail first, then confirmed passing):\n- `user@mail..example.com` → rejected (the reported bounce case)\n- `ada@mail.example.com` → accepted (guards against over-correcting and breaking legitimate multi-label domains)\n\n`npm test`: 4/4 passing."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":371,"cache_read_input_tokens":28965,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":371},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8341789d-7d94-432d-bf6c-fce68013f0fd","uuid":"68890bef-7e23-402f-a7c5-388d43469351","timestamp":"2026-07-22T14:02:14.663Z","request_id":"req_011CdHDfmh2fYUYfSw7Q4n8g"}
